an style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> stepping down</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Higher s</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">taff turnover </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">is not necessarily a direct consequence of </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">a negative in</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">pection.</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">  A</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> change p</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">rogramme</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">, like those</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> put in place after an O</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">fsted inspection</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> may in itself be linked to increased staff turnover, as suggested in the Audit Commission re</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">port (2002)</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> particularly if</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> change is perceived by staff to be ‘imposed’ and ‘irrelevant’ to their day to day work. </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Other issues may also be at play, but there needs to be further thought given to the </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">impact of inspections o</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">n retaining high-quality staff. The loss of</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> trained staff may lead to further issues on already struggling services.</span></li><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Staff turnover is a </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">critical</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> issue and we would draw the Committee’s attention to the research</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">, particularly from the US, </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">linking a high staff turnover to poor out</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">comes for children </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">and families</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">The way staff turnover is linked to poor outcomes is not linear: it may </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">increas</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">e work</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">load</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">for remaining staff, </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">reduc</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">e availability of</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> the peer-to-peer support</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">and loss of experienced </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">staff</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">.  In addi</span><span style="font-famil