mplications, </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">leads to </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">negative </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">attention from the media</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> and therefore </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">from </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">a very wide audience</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">, and</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> affect</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> job security.</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">  </span></li><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Th</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> effect</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">s of an Ofsted inspection in the culture of children’s services</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> should not be undermined. The</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">re is a</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> general feeling in the sector of </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">it leading to </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">a cu</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">lture of </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">attributing</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> blame.  Research has previously pointed to the shift in a way of working in children’s services that is “</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">defensible” </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">rather than </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">focused on </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">making the right decisions for the right children and families, particularly in the wake of inq</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">uiries and audits.  Authors such as Banks (1995) and Parton (2005) pointed to the shift towards a culture of following procedure to protect </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">workers</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> from blame.  In such environment, focus on achieving the best outcomes for children can easily be lost.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Th</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">e importance of an organisation’s culture is widely substantiated by evidence, especially from the US, </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">linking</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> a positive organisational culture </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">with</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">lower staff turnover and intention to leave</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> and</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">even the </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">ability of staff to adopt evidence based </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">programmes in practice</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">.  This has in turn been linke</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">d to better performance and bett</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">er outcomes for children being achieved.</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Some studies place a </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">positive </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">organisational</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> culture </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">as more</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> important for the quality and outcome</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">s of children’s service systems</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">t</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">han interorganis</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">ational coordination</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">We would submit that this body of research needs to be given more </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">attention</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">considering the </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">impact of Ofs</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">t</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">d inspections </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">and whether they</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> are compatible </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">with </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">positive organisational culture, where learning is paramount.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">The role of Ofsted on sector improvement is also something we would argue deserves further consideration.  Inspections could and should be a useful mechanism by which improvement can be achiev</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">ed.  This is something that is already occurring in other sectors and we would see it as a useful opportunity to support the sector and achieve improvement.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">A final comment we would like to add regards the quality of inspections, and the need to ensure pr</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">oper training and support provided to Ofsted inspectors to achieve good quality, meaningful inspections</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">, routed in the realities of the sector</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">.  We would hope this would form part of any review of the role of Ofsted in social care.</span><a name="_GoBack"></a></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">January 2014</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#x